text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!American Promise: Idiris Code Switches%0a%0a:Author: AlexisA%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI share a video of a black student who attends Dalton explaining how he is made fun of by his peers in his neighborhood for talking "like a white boy."%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zz-PyvtgCmQ%0a%0aThe above is a short clip from "American Promise," a documentary that follows two black boys through their experience at Dalton (one of the most prestigious private schools in the United States). In the video, one of the boys, Idris, explains that he is made fun of by some of the kids on his neighborhood basketball team because he "talk[s] like a white boy." %0a%0aIdris explains that he sometimes changes his dialect when in his primarily black neighborhood in order to blend in, using the example heɪjɒ̞ɔl: wʌs:ʌp for "hey y'all, what's up?" to simulate a version of African American Vernacular English. In particular, this example represents a lowering of the [ɔ] sound in y'all and consonant deletion between the final two words. Throughout the rest of the clip, he uses Standard American English.%0a%0aI chose this example, in part, because I thought it was interesting how it did not conform to our typical ideas about power dynamics in the context of linguistic discrimination. Rather than a person of privilege/power attempting to enforce the standards of their dialect on another person, it shows an example of people discriminating against another dialect because it represents a departure from what they consider normal for their community. I also wonder if it may reflect power dynamics in a different way, such as the members of his neighborhood feeling threatened that their teammate has access to different experiences and privileges than they do.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210415-162723-320480#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Additional discussion %0a-> - abbyl%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI agree with you that the discrimination of people who talk in Standard American English in a community that speaks in another dialect could be because the community feels threatened. I think that the existing power dynamic between Standard American English, a dialect in the superstratum, and dialects such as AAVE, which are in the substratum, may cause communities such as Idris's to think that people speaking in Standard American English are giving a verbal signal of superiority. Speaking in Standard American English could cause these communities to think that the people speaking Standard American English are flaunting their access to more opportunities and privilege, making the communities feel defensive about their own social status. Moreover, I think that these communities could also be feeling a sense of abandonment when someone who grew up in the community suddenly rejects the community's dialect in favor of Standard American English.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210415-162723-320480#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
